snippet.title: #97 Teach your Child to Stand on Her Own: Exercises for a Baby with Low Tone
snippet.description:
I am producing this video series with my co-instructor, Myla Sunshine, who is a beautiful girl who has low tone and Down syndrome. She lives 250 miles from my house. Her parents were nice enough to allow me, a perfect stranger, to come in and share their daughter with the world. Thank you, again. My name is Amy Sturkey. I am a pediatric physical therapist from the United States. I hope to follow Myla as she develops. I hope to teach ideas to help her learn to move, crawl, sit and walk. I started this video series after questions came in from all over the world from people seeking assistance in helping children with low tone. The ideas I teach in this video are not appropriate for a much weaker child than the one featured in this video. I hope you find this idea useful and simple. 

My website is www.pediatricPTexercises.com  My Facebook page is Pediatric Physical Therapy Exercises. My informational books, "A is for Autism,"  "C is for Cerebral Palsy," "D is for Down Syndrome," "Pediatric Physical Therapy Strengthening Exercises for the Hips"  and "Pediatric Physical Therapy Strengthening Exercises for the Knees" are available on Amazon. "A is for ADHD" should be available shortly. Do not hesitate to contact me at amysturkey@gmail.com with questions, concerns or favorable reviews! Please note I am unable to provide treatment recommendations for a child I have not personally evaluated.

I am so honored to have people from all over the world watch my videos. I have reviewed and corrected the closed captions for this video so that you might understand what I am saying even if you don't speak English. I hope the directions below are helpful to you.

snippet.title: Child Development Make At Home Activity: Finger Strength Exercises
snippet.description:
Braille Institute Child Development Consultant Liz shares a finger strength exercise to practice with children who are visually impaired. This exercise will help increase their finger strength in preparation for reading and writing braille and exploring their world through touch. Full instructions below:

Instructions:
Have your child play with the material. Pinch, pull, and poke. You can show them how to:
1. Roll material into a ball
2. Practice rolling it into a snake
3. Make a rope and pinch pieces off and pull to work on pincer grasp
4. Use safety or play-doh scissors and butter knife WITH SUPERVISION 
5. Hide a small toy under it for them to find
6. Poke with one finger to work on finger isolation
7. Show your child how to push their fingertips through to make a handprint

Materials:
Play-Doh
Theraputty
Plastic knife
Plastic or safety scissors

snippet.title: Child Development Make At Home Activity: Feelings & Emotions Exercise
snippet.description:
Braille Institute Child Development Consultant Elizabeth has another make at home activity for children who are visually impaired, this one teaching children how to talk and communicate how they are feeling. 

Feelings and Emotions
Objective: 
• To teach the child to talk and communicate how they are feeling. For non-verbal children pictures are a great way for them to express their feelings. They can point to the picture of pick the card. 

Suggested Materials:
• Paper with face drawings 
• Wikki Stix
• Puffy Paint
• School Glue
• Hot Glue 

Instructions:
• Print or draw faces on paper, it can be construction paper or cardstock
• Add texture with the material of choice (wikki stix/ glue/ puffy paint)
• Have child explore the pictures with hands and talk about what they feel
• Add other prompts such as songs “If you are happy and you know it”

snippet.title: Workout with your kids
snippet.description: http://www.facebook.com/pressplaytoday    http://www.twitter.com/lisakingslayer   As a busy mom, I make it a priority to not only spend time with my family when work allows, but to spend QUALITY and active time with them.  My daughter Faith is featured in this video with me because she really enjoys working out with mommy.  I do not even have to ask her.  I just say, I'm going to workout and there she is... my little shadow.  My daughter Phoebe on the other hand is a tad more laid back.  However, both of my children know how important living a healthy lifestyle is.  I am not a psycho forcing them to lose weight.  I simply feed them a balanced diet, and get them moving.  I refuse to let my children follow in my childhood footsteps of ever eating... weight problems and being teased for the same.  I hope that you can get a little laugh out of this at some points, and that maybe it inspires you to get up and moving with your own children.  The workout featured herein is Les Mills COMBAT Power HIIT.  If you have not checked this program out, I highly recommend it.  Great results in very little time. snippet.title: #35 Switch Adapted Toys 1 of 2: Exercises for a Child with Cerebral Palsy
snippet.description:
Meet Sebastian. He is a young boy with Spastic Quadriplegic Cerebral Palsy. His family wants to help me share treatment suggestions to help children like him across the world.  My clinic, Child and Family Development,  in Charlotte, NC, allowed me to use their facilities and their equipment to showcase Sebastian's skill and charming personality. We review techniques to reduce stiffness, encourage strength and control. I think you'll love spending time with him. Thank you to this family and my clinic for allowing this to happen.
 I also have available 3 children's educational books, "A is for Autism," "D is for Down Syndrome," "C is for Cerebral Palsy,"   and now 2 professional books "Pediatric Physical Therapy Exercises for the Hips", and "Pediatric Physical Therapy Exercises for the Knees" available on Amazon.  I have forthcoming "A is for ADHD" as well.  If you have questions or suggestions, feel free to contact me at amysturkey@gmail.com. Please note: I am unable to provide treatment suggestions for a child I have not personally evaluated.
I am so honored to have people from all over the world watch my videos. I have reviewed and corrected the closed captions for this video so that you might understand what I am saying even if you don't speak English. I hope the directions below are helpful to you.

To choose a different caption language:
At the bottom right, click Settings. It looks like a wheel.
Click Subtitles/CC.
Select a language.
If the language isn't listed when you click Subtitles/CC:
Click Auto-translate.
Select a language.

snippet.title: Letters of the Alphabet | Capital Letters | Uppercase Letters | Alphabet Workout | Jack Hartmann
snippet.description:
Alphabet Workout strengthens alphabet recognition, letter formation skills and fitness of your class.  My Alphabet Workout song - Upper Case follows the Zaner - Bloser instructions for writing the upper case letters to develop the exercise movements and verbal letter formation directions. 

This song incorporates visual, auditory and kinesthetic learning. Gross motor movements are used to form the letters to enhance physical activity. Children follow my movements as I form the upper case letters of the alphabet. 

The more we engage our children in movement, the more we really are strengthening their health and well-being. I made the letters as large as possible so your children can clearly see and watch me form the letters. 

Play this song every day to help your children get great practice forming the letters and making body and brain connections.

Brain and Body Builders DVD:
http://www.jackhartmann.com/brain-and-body-builders/

snippet.title: Fun Phonics Fitness Song | Letter Sounds for Kids | Exercise Song | Jack Hartmann
snippet.description:
This letter sound song is a fun way of exercising your body and your brain to the letter sounds.  Say the letters, the letter sound and a word that begins with each letter sound as you build your body and your brain by doing different exercises to each group of letter sounds and alphabet recognition.    We incorporate lots of cross body movements to build brain and body connections while building fitness and phonics skills.  This movement song for kids will encourage active and engaged learning while learning about letter sounds.  Fun Phonics Fitness Song.

snippet.title: Monsters In The Dark | Little Angel Kids Songs & Nursery Rhymes
snippet.description:
Nighttime can be a very scary time.  Monsters lurk in the shadows, and ghosts hide in the closet.  No need to be afraid Baby John, you aren’t afraid of the dark.   Enjoy this new version of the Monsters In The Dark and other exciting songs. #littleangel  #littleangelnurseryrhymes  #babyjohnsongs  #babyjohnnurseryrhymes

(🔔) Subscribe to Little Angel for new videos ►► http://bit.ly/Subscribe_to_LittleAngel 

List of Kids Songs;
00:04 I Don't Like Being Alone In The Dark
03:59 This is The Way I Get Dressed 
07:53 Be Safe! Wash Your Hands
11:12 Yes Yes Fruits Are Good For You
15:17 Exercise Song
18:55 No More Snacks Baby John

Song Lyrics 

Now we are alone,
All alone in the dark
What’s that shadow? What could it be? 
It looks like a monster to me

Let’s check and see
Where is it coming from?
It must be a monster, I’m afraid
Phew! It was just in our heads

Once upon a time
there was a big/scary wolf 
howling so loud and its eyes so bright
No one came out at night.

Look it’s dark outside,
we’re alone in the dark.
What’s that noise, behind the door?
Now I can’t see anymore

Oh no, who’s there?
Do you see what I see?
It’s so creepy! I’m so scared
We hide all and then we all wait

There it was again
I need to go and check
Let’s be brave, let’s find out 
Phew, just a bush outside

Oh I am so scared
Let’s stay here and wait
No, no go, stay with us
it’s so scary out there

There it was again
What’s behind that door?
Just a toy car/ shining at night 
No need to be afraid

Something just moved!
It’s getting closer to us
it’s so scary, I’m so scared
I’m sure it’s not in my head

What was that noise?
Looks like a branch to me
It’s not a monster, just a tree
No need to be afraid
